node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 16, 2021. May be an image of table, chandelier and living room.

node.text:
“Art to me is not about having a wall to fill,” says designer and owner of this Seattle home, Brian Paquette (@brian.paquette_), who studied conceptual art and painting. “I buy it because I have an [eternal] connection to it, like you just seemingly can’t live without it. You feel like it’s a ghost limb that you didn’t know you had.” Paquette is drawn to the work of Seattle artist @lakshmimuirhead, and one of her abstract paintings hangs on the wall of the dining room. On Seattle’s signature gray days, a chandelier from New York’s @apparatusstudio, which is made of glass orbs, fills this space with warm light.

Tour every space at our bio link. Photo by @aaronleitz; design by @brian.paquette_; words by Jennifer Flowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 16, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
“He saw the built environment as a way to connect people and lives,” notes Stuart Graff, president and CEO of the Frank Lloyd Wright Foundation (@wrighttaliesin). Today the organization is looking to the past and future, endeavoring to, as Graff explains, “present Wright in ways that encourage people to take his ideas and act on them.”

Learn more about the future of Wright's Taliesin at our bio link. Photo by John Miller and Hedrich Blessing; words by @samuelcochran.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 15, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
For the interiors of this home on Lake Austin, designer Emily Seiders (@studioseiders) took cues from the clients’ personalities and stories about their travels (“they loved Soho Farmhouse in Oxfordshire and enjoy spending time in Manhattan”) in order to come up with a design that’s easy yet refined with just a touch of whimsy. “We were not chasing trends, and that’s something hard to do in this digital age,” says Seiders. “I wanted to create a home that’s livable but very special, with a whole lot of attention to detail.”

Explore every space at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @ryanstreetarchitects and @studioseiders; words by @whatpaolasees.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, credenza and indoor.

node.text:
Designs of this Monaco duplex were commissioned to complement the clients' art collection. “We are most proud of the balance between our interior design and their collection,” architect @emilhumbert says of a light fixture by the @bouroullecbrothers. “Everything works together…. The challenge was to make the place [feel] full of life within this modern building.” Sitting atop a 1950s Brazilian cabinet by Martin Eisler and Carlo Hauner are ceramic pieces by French artist Georges Jouve, a sculpture by American artist Sherrie Levine, and a 19th-century Venetian vase. The Jean Prouvé armchair is complemented by work by @theastergates and a painting by South African artist @cinga_samson.

See the home at our bio link. Photo by @francisamiand; design by @humbertetpoyet; words by @gaygassmann.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 15, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
Throughout Reni Folawiyo's penthouse in Lagos are several pieces by Jérôme Abel Seguin, like this bench under the staircase crafted from a single piece of tigerwood. Seguin's industrial coffee tables from Indonesia were so heavy that they had to be brought in by crane. “I knew that Jérôme’s pieces would help form the core of my home,” Folawiyo says. “I’ve been dreaming of collecting his work for years.” Seguin has said that he “creates objects that cry out to be caressed.” So, naturally, one can’t help but stroke the mahogany-root console standing in a nook. 

Explore the exquisite home at our bio link. Photo by @iamdanielobasi; design by @__okha; architecture by @_saota; words by @lolaogunnaike.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 14, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
“I love the study,” says Janice, the owner of her generational home in coastal Maine. “It’s that room where I like to go and read a book or do a puzzle.” The room features a 19th-century mahogany breakfast table found at a local antiques shop. This portion of the study features a built-in bench that’s perfect for curling up with a good mystery book.

Step inside the home at our bio link. Photo by @darrensetlow; design by @knickerbockergroup; words by @robertbythebook.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 14, 2021. May be an image of bedroom.

node.text:
This 18th-century colonial farmhouse is an amalgam of objects from different generations, aesthetic and familial. Louis XV–style dining chairs from the Mississippi Delta home of homeowner and painter @marynelsonsinclair’s grandmother mingle beside a bar table draped with a peach-hued suzani from her mother’s house in Dallas that matches the blush wall color. Her bedroom with husband and sculptor Matty Cruise (@corbincruise) features an eclectic array of textiles.

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @gievesanderson; design by Mary Louise; styling by @mieketenhave; words by @chloemalle.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 14, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Slowly, remotely over the course of the pandemic, the vision of @jesshart's L.A. home began to reveal itself. A combination of Moroccan, Turkish, and Italian design influences, the global mélange is held together by stripes and botanical patterns throughout. In the dining room, Floyd, the family’s Yorkshire Terrier, perches on a vintage dining chair.

Tour her home at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @casamotachic; words by @carly_olson.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 13, 2021. May be an image of furniture and kitchen.

node.text:
“Most of the stuff in my home, aside from a few pieces, are things I already had when we moved into the house,” says designer Brian Paquette (@brian.paquette_) of his Seattle home, referring to pieces picked up at Manhattan furniture stores, Parisian flea markets, and everywhere in between. “They’re all things I really love without context for exact space.” Paquette added the wood-and-steel table extension to the kitchen’s existing marble island. The open shelves display everyday ceramics, including Japanese Hasami porcelain. 

Tour every space at our bio link. Photo by @aaronleitz; design by @brian.paquette_; words by Jennifer Flowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 13, 2021. May be an image of furniture.

node.text:
Monegasque interior architect @christophe_poyet_ and Parisian architect @emilhumbert are known for their cool take on elegance. So it’s no huge wonder that their namesake firm has been writing the book on comfortable glamour for the past 14 years. And though Humbert & Poyet have spearheaded projects from Dubai to Hong Kong to Mexico, this particularly special 8,600-square-foot duplex apartment is in their own backyard.

See the Monaco home at our bio link. Photo by @francisamiand; design by @humbertetpoyet; words by @gaygassmann.
